Q2: Create a scatterplot of diamond price vs.Â table and color the points by the cut of the diamond.

ggplot(aes(x=table,y=price,color=cut),data=diamonds)+
  geom_point(aes(color=cut))+scale_color_brewer(type='qual')

Note: in Q1, we use scale_fill_brewer to set the theme of color, but in Q2 we use scale_color_brewer.

Q4:

Create a scatterplot of diamond price vs.Â volume (x * y * z) and color the points by the clarity of diamonds. Use scale on the y-axis to take the log10 of price. You should also omit the top 1% of diamond volumes from the plot.

Note: Volume is a very rough approximation of a diamondâ€™s actual volume.

Note: In the link, a color palette of type â€˜divâ€™ was used to color the scatterplot using scale_color_brewer(type = 'div')

Note: quantile(diamonds$vol,0.99) is different from 0.99*max(diamonds$vol). The former takes the last 99% of the rank, while the later one takes 0.99 of the maximum value.

diamonds$vol=with(diamonds,x*y*z)
s_diamonds=subset(diamonds,vol<quantile(diamonds$vol,0.99))
ggplot(aes(x=vol,y=price,color=clarity),data=s_diamonds)+geom_point()+scale_y_log10()+scale_color_brewer(type = 'div')
